b'Rounding out our Local Love series: architect Kimberly Neuhaus. As a child, Neuhaus spent time in her father\xe2\x80\x99s office and quickly decided that architects had the best toys. As an adult, she still brings that same joy to every project as she discovers old buildings and adapts them to life in the 21st century.

Together with the other members of her office, Karin Ames and Sadi Dhakhwa, the team have 56 years of professional experience between them. Between them, they\xe2\x80\x99ve noticed many misconceptions about the work they do; \xe2\x80\x9cpeople often assume architects make a lot of money\xe2\x80\x9d Neuhaus explains, adding \xe2\x80\x9cat the same time they often underestimate the value that we bring to a project.\xe2\x80\x9d

Life at Neuhaus Design Architecture has changed dramatically as a result of Covid-19. The team began working remotely just before shut down, thinking that the change might last a week or two. Then they adapted again, changing their lease to be month to month before finally giving up the space and deciding to become a virtual office. And, as the future remains uncertain, the company has also had to keep on adapting \xe2\x80\x9cwe want to be cautious and prioritize salaries and healthcare over rent\xe2\x80\x9d.

That resiliency is also one of Neuhaus\xe2\x80\x99 favorite things about the city of New York. She first visited from Texas at the age of 13 \xe2\x80\x9cI told my parents then that I wanted to live here someday. I came for college and never left.\xe2\x80\x9d

The Coach Foundation is proud to support small businesses like @neuhausdesignarchitecture in partnership with NYC Department of Small Business Services (SBS) through its contribution to the NYC Small Business Continuity Loan Fund. To learn more visit @nycsmallbiz.

To date, the Coach Foundation has committed more than $4 million in COVID-19 relief efforts globally including @nycsmallbiz and @montefiorehealthsystem. The Coach brand has also donated over $3.5 million worth of product to healthcare frontline responders and raised over $200,000 to date for Feeding America, donating 100% of net profit from Coach Face Masks sold in the U.S.

b'Chef Keesha O\xe2\x80\x99Galdez, the next New Yorker in our Local Love series, is used to big life changes. When the financial crisis happened in 2008, O\xe2\x80\x99Galdez had been working as a consultant at Bank of America in Boston and lost her job. Rather than losing hope, she saw an opportunity to escape the traditional 9 to 5 life and pursue her passion in cooking and it wasn\xe2\x80\x99t long before Gourmet Diva was born. O\xe2\x80\x99Galdez has spent the last nine years working in the food industry as everything from a pastry chef to a freelance caterer for some of New York\xe2\x80\x99s most prestigious companies.

Now that Covid has disrupted the food industry as we know it, O\xe2\x80\x99Galdez has shifted once again. \xe2\x80\x9cI had to put on hold the majority of services I offered\xe2\x80\xa6 I had to reinvent and figure out how I can still be connected and entertain people in a safe manner.\xe2\x80\x9d Her solution: to build a company that offers both education and entertainment around food.

As a born and raised New Yorker, O\xe2\x80\x99Galdez believes the city has shaped her to become the resilient person she is today. \xe2\x80\x9cThere is an intensity and drive that we have that you don\xe2\x80\x99t get anywhere else\xe2\x80\x9d O\xe2\x80\x99Galdez explains. As for the future, she remains hopeful, buoyed by the outpouring of support the city has shown for small businesses like hers.

b"\xe2\x80\x9cFor many New Yorkers, the hunger crisis was their normal before the pandemic. Just ask Sultana Ocasio, next in our Local Love series. Ocasio's job is all about addressing that crisis: \xe2\x80\x9cI love how simple it is to give people food and take that burden away from them.\xe2\x80\x9d And, she adds, there\xe2\x80\x99s joy in that too. \xe2\x80\x9cWhen folks feel that sense of security, a natural hospitality kicks in. They cook and share with their families and neighbors.\xe2\x80\x9d

Ocasio is the director of Food Bank for New York City\xe2\x80\x99s Community Kitchen and Food Pantry in Harlem. Her job involves making sure that teams are able to distribute food to the largest number of people in need that they possibly can. And, since Covid began, distributing that food safely has become an even higher priority. The need to socially distance and quarantine has been challenging, but it\xe2\x80\x99s also given Ocasio hope. \xe2\x80\x9cOur distance has shown us how much we need each other and has actually driven us closer to each other emotionally. We realized that we need each other to get through this. We already knew that hunger was wrong. Now we see more acutely how we're connected.\xe2\x80\x9d

There is beauty everywhere in New York, Ocasio believes all we have to do is be willing to notice; \xe2\x80\x9cI like watching the East River heave, the bellow of a good laugh, and looking up from the sidewalk and randomly seeing a pretty bird on 116th St. If I can still appreciate those things, I know there's no space for despair.\xe2\x80\x9d

Coach is proud to support Feeding America and their work delivering food to communities who need it. To learn more visit @foodbank4nyc, a member of @feedingamerica and their national network.

:writing_hand_selector: & :artist_palette: by @monachalabi"

b'"People always think that as critical care physicians, we spend all of our time resuscitating patients and responding to emergencies,\xe2\x80\x9d says Dr. Michele Ng Gong, next in our Local Love series. It\xe2\x80\x99s true\xe2\x80\x94she explains\xe2\x80\x94it *is* part of her job. But the bigger part of it, where she spends more of her time and gets more of her satisfaction, comes from talking with families and preventing and preparing for emergencies.

Of course, the biggest emergency that healthcare providers have faced has been this pandemic\xe2\x80\x94and the hospital where Dr Gong works has been at the center of that. Montefiore and Einstein have treated almost a quarter of the cases of Covid-19 in New York state and that includes patients that are struggling due to population density, poverty levels, and prevalence of underlying health conditions. As well as providing that direct care, Montefiore and Einstein have been leading in research; the hospital has conducted the largest-scale pediatric study into COVID-19 in the country.

That desire to solve problems is one of the things that first attracted Dr Gong to medicine - the special combination of science and care (or what Dr Gong describes as \xe2\x80\x9cthe privilege of helping people\xe2\x80\x9d). It\xe2\x80\x99s not just how she works though; it\xe2\x80\x99s where. Dr Gong loves practicing medicine here in New York. \xe2\x80\x9cIn spite of its size, New York City is still a community\xe2\x80\xa6 We hurt together and we rise together.\xe2\x80\x9d

The Coach Foundation is proud to support Montefiore and their work in healthcare. To learn more visit @montefiorehealthsystem.

To date, the Coach Foundation has committed more than $4 million in COVID-19 relief efforts globally including @nycsmallbiz and @montefiorehealthsystem. The Coach brand has also donated over $3.5 million worth of product to healthcare frontline responders and raised over $200,000 to date for Feeding America, donating 100% of net profit from Coach Face Masks sold in the U.S.

b'Next in our Local Love series: civil engineer, Sebastian Aguas Lozano. Lozano\xe2\x80\x99s parents were civil engineers\xe2\x80\x94some of his earliest memories are of hanging out on job sites, spaces about to be changed by construction. \xe2\x80\x9cI was always impressed by the transformation,\xe2\x80\x9d Lozano says. He knew he wanted to follow in his parents footsteps.

Now, Lozano has spent seven years working as a civil engineer in construction, and three years with his own business, @ecg_renovations. He still finds the job satisfying, especially here in New York where he has found opportunity, success and joy.

But people often misunderstand his work. There\xe2\x80\x99s a tendency to focus on the construction process, but for Lozano that\xe2\x80\x99s just the very last stage. Before any brick is laid, \xe2\x80\x9cthere is a lot of time and effort involved in design, feasibility, budgeting, coordination and project managing\xe2\x80\x9d, Lozano explains. So, when Covid-19 began, it wasn\xe2\x80\x99t only the construction part of Lozano\xe2\x80\x99s business that had to be changed, \xe2\x80\x9cwe had to reinvent the way we work to create a free and safe environment for our staff and subcontractors.\xe2\x80\x9d

Despite the economic impact, Lozano remains hopeful about the future. He looks forward to continuing to transform spaces in the city he loves.

The Coach Foundation is proud to support small businesses like @ecg_renovations in partnership with NYC Department of Small Business Services (SBS) through its contribution to the NYC Small Business Continuity Loan Fund. To learn more visit @nycsmallbiz.

b'Introducing Local Love\xe2\x80\x93a series that celebrates the people keeping communities vibrant, today and always. Community is everything at Coach. This week, we\xe2\x80\x99re sharing stories of resilience from our hometown, New York \xe2\x80\x93 as told to a data journalist and illustrator, @MonaChalabi. Tune in to read stories about New Yorkers running small businesses, working in healthcare and delivering food to those who need it \xe2\x80\x93 all from organizations Coach and the Coach Foundation have supported throughout COVID-19 including @nycsmallbiz, @montefiorehealthsystem and @feedingamerica.

Ryan Gil, RN, is pretty new to nursing but he\xe2\x80\x99s a veteran of New York City. So, when his professional life was shaken by the Covid-19 pandemic, he felt comforted by the fact that he was surrounded by driven, resilient, fellow New Yorkers.

\xe2\x80\x9cCOVID-19 came around, and anxiety was at an all time high\xe2\x80\x9d. Thankfully, things have improved considerably in the city but Gil still maintains the same vigilance at work. He says that focusing on hygiene has allowed him to \xe2\x80\x9ckeep my head level\xe2\x80\x9d, as well as the knowledge that he is helping members of his Hispanic community in the low-income neighborhood of the Bronx where he grew up.

But the medical care teams at Montefiore and Einstein rely on philanthropic generosity in order to keep on treating patients, preventing the spread of disease and innovating solutions. By donating to the Critical Response Care Fund, you can support immediate needs including supplies, equipment, transportation, research, and more\xe2\x80\x94ultimately, helping to halt this pandemic.

b"Today we honor. Next week we act.
.
.
Today we commemorate Juneteenth as a paid company holiday and stand in solidarity with the Black community. We honor the Black lives who fought for freedom and those who continue to fight for racial equality and justice. Next week, we'll share with you our first partnership to counter systemic racism. We know there is no easy fix, but we are committed to long-term, action-driven solutions to help end racism once and for all."

b'From systemic racism to modern-day activism to having hope, our chief executive spoke about why it\xe2\x80\x99s time \xe2\x80\x9cto focus on the cause.\xe2\x80\x9d Sound up to hear his full interview. And as always, tell us what you think. We\xe2\x80\x99re listening.
.
.
.
We are in the process of partnering with a number of social justice, legal, and corporate entities to formulate a longer-term plan for addressing systemic inequality. Until then, we want to continue the Black Lives Matter conversation and use this platform as a space to amplify Black voices.'

b"Comment below if there is a non-profit, an initiative, an educational resource, or an individual that is driving change and equality for Black communities that you'd like to amplify.\n\xe2\x80\xa8In the words of our CEO, Jide Zeitlin: \xe2\x80\x9cThe time is now for meaningful action and we are in the process of partnering with a number of social justice, legal, and corporate entities to formulate a longer-term plan for addressing systemic inequality.\xe2\x80\x9d Until then, we want to continue the Black Lives Matter conversation and use this platform as a space to amplify Black voices."

b'\xe2\x80\x93\xe2\x80\x93\xe2\x80\x9cToday, we\xc2\xa0continue to\xc2\xa0mourn the incalculable loss of\xc2\xa0George Floyd, Ahmaud Arbery, Breonna Taylor, Eric Garner, Trayvon Martin, Emmett Till, and too many others.\xc2\xa0Black Lives Matter.

At Coach we lead with our hearts and values, and stand up for the social issues we believe in. The events unfolding right now are also deeply personal to me.

This\xc2\xa0past\xc2\xa0weekend, I re-read Martin Luther King Jr.\xe2\x80\x99s 1963 \xe2\x80\x9cLetter from a Birmingham Jail.\xe2\x80\x9d Almost 60 years have passed, yet America is still struggling to solve a 400-year-old problem.\xc2\xa0In a moment where we must all reflect honestly about our nation\xe2\x80\x99s history of racial injustice, we have asked ourselves \xe2\x80\x93 what can we do to drive change and put an end to systemic inequality?

Together, we stand with my fellow Black employees, customers, partners and the Black community as a whole. The time is now for meaningful action and we are in the process of partnering with a number of social justice, legal, and corporate entities to formulate a longer-term plan for addressing systemic inequality.\xc2\xa0More to follow soon on the actions we\xc2\xa0are\xc2\xa0taking.

I believe that we will stand taller if we all stand together, lead with compassion, and commit to change that creates a fair and just future for all.\xe2\x80\x9d \xe2\x80\x94Jide Zeitlin, @Tapestry CEO

#BlackLivesMatter'
